WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.800
So, I'm going to share some data looking at the feasibility of rapid dose escalation

00:00:05.800 --> 00:00:10.280
scheduled Bispecific for relapsed refractory large B-cell lymphoma.

00:00:11.800 --> 00:00:12.060
Okay.

00:00:12.520 --> 00:00:18.820
So, for people less familiar with the lymphoma bispecifics, EPCORIDOMAB and GLOFIDOMAB are

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:23.840
CD20-CD3 Bispecific approved for use in relapsed refractory large B-cell lymphoma.

00:00:24.160 --> 00:00:30.180
And in pivotal trials, CRS occurs in about 50% to 60% of patients treated with EPCORIDOMAB

00:00:30.180 --> 00:00:35.120
and GLOFIDOMAB monotherapy, and ICANS in about 6% to 8% of patients.

00:00:36.100 --> 00:00:41.420
And to mitigate the risk of CRS in ICANS, we use step-up dosing in addition to a pretreatment

00:00:41.420 --> 00:00:43.500
dose of obinutuzumab prior to GLOFIDOMAB.

00:00:44.180 --> 00:00:48.580
However, this, of course, delays the first full dose of therapeutic Bispecific

00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:50.780
till day 15 and 22, respectively.

00:00:51.540 --> 00:00:53.780
And for patients with very proliferative lymphoma,

00:00:54.160 --> 00:00:57.600
the rate of progression may outpace step-up dosing,

00:00:58.040 --> 00:01:01.280
necessitating earlier delivery of the first full dose of Bispecific.

00:01:03.100 --> 00:01:03.540
Okay.

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.080
So, this was the impetus for a rapid dose escalation schedule of EPCORIDOMAB at my institution,

00:01:08.480 --> 00:01:09.580
which is shown here.

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:11.940
So, we give EPCORIDOMAB on day 1, 4, 7.

00:01:12.260 --> 00:01:15.920
Each dose is preceded by a clinic visit, and then EPCORIDOMAB is given outpatient.

00:01:16.580 --> 00:01:20.840
And on day 7, patients are admitted to the hospital for a minimum of 24 hours,

00:01:20.940 --> 00:01:23.100
although hopefully this will be changing in the future.

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:23.180
Okay.

00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:27.020
Patients get dexamethasone, 16 milligrams, on days 1 through 11.

00:01:27.600 --> 00:01:31.880
And then they're also sent home with a pill-in-pocket steroid dose of 12 milligrams

00:01:31.880 --> 00:01:34.860
with instructions to take their temperature twice daily

00:01:34.860 --> 00:01:38.460
if they have a fever, to take the dexamethasone, and then call a clinic.

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:46.300
And after treating the first 10 patients with this step-up dosing schedule,

00:01:46.520 --> 00:01:50.380
we reported CRS in 50% of the patients.

00:01:50.380 --> 00:01:53.460
And you can see eight of them had large B-cell lymphoma and 2-CLL.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.900
And importantly, there were no grade 3 or higher rates of CRS,

00:01:57.180 --> 00:02:00.540
and there were no reported cases of ICANS.

00:02:01.940 --> 00:02:06.440
And this was particularly relevant for us because the University of Utah

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:09.120
is the largest referral center in the Mountain West United States.

00:02:09.600 --> 00:02:12.640
And among the six patients that were residing outside of Utah,

00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:15.640
four of them were able to return back to their referring provider.

00:02:17.640 --> 00:02:22.060
So, this also, you know, laid the foundation for a much larger multi-institutional study.

00:02:22.960 --> 00:02:26.120
And this was a multi-center retrospective study of real-world patients

00:02:26.120 --> 00:02:29.280
with non-Hodgkin lymphoma treated with EBCO or Glofit

00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:33.160
at nine centers in the collaborative U.S. bispecific consortium, which we call QBIC.

00:02:33.960 --> 00:02:37.780
And we defined a rapid dose escalation schedule as omission of obinutuzumab

00:02:37.780 --> 00:02:41.480
in the case of glofitumab and or a dose escalation schedule

00:02:41.480 --> 00:02:46.000
with at least one step-up dosing interval that was shorter than the standard of care dosing.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:50.420
And we compared patients treated on a rapid dose escalation schedule

00:02:50.420 --> 00:02:52.940
to a time-matched cohort of patients treated with EBCO.

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:55.180
EBCO or Glofit on a non-rapid schedule.

00:02:56.180 --> 00:02:58.980
And then, importantly, a comment about our statistics.

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:06.700
So, we used a propensity score matching analysis to balance relevant clinical variables

00:03:06.700 --> 00:03:12.400
and additionally did a sensitivity analysis using inverse propensity weighting

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:16.520
to strengthen this primary analysis.

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:22.520
So, in total, we...

00:03:22.960 --> 00:03:26.520
Identified 38 patients that were treated with a rapid dose escalation schedule

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:30.240
and 307 treated on a standard dose escalation schedule.

00:03:30.900 --> 00:03:35.400
And these are the baseline characteristics at Bispecific start in the unmatched cohort.

00:03:36.100 --> 00:03:39.980
And the important thing I want to point out is that the rapid patients were enriched with high-risk features

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:44.920
and they had significantly more high-grade B-cell lymphoma patients

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:47.280
and patients with an elevated LDH.

00:03:49.200 --> 00:03:52.180
So, among the 12 patients that were treated with a rapid dose escalation schedule,

00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:58.260
with EBCO, the median time from step-up dose 1 to the first full dose of EBCO was 6 days.

00:03:58.260 --> 00:04:01.460
And the most common regimen was day 1, 4, and 7.

00:04:01.460 --> 00:04:05.460
And then, among the 26 patients that were treated with Glofit on a rapid schedule,

00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:09.220
the median time from step-up dose 1 to the first full dose was 14 days.

00:04:09.220 --> 00:04:13.460
And the two most common regimens were either omission of obinutuzumab

00:04:13.460 --> 00:04:18.420
and day 1 obinutuzumab with step-up dose 1 on day 3.

00:04:18.420 --> 00:04:21.280
In the unmatched cohort,

00:04:21.280 --> 00:04:28.760
the rates of CRS in the rapid group were 47% and about 38% in the standard group.

00:04:28.760 --> 00:04:35.360
And the rates of ICANNs in the rapid group was 21% and about 13% in the standard group.

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:39.600
However, I want to point out that in the case of both CRS and ICANNs,

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:46.080
most cases were grade 1 or 2 and the rates of grade 3 or higher CRS and ICANNs

00:04:46.080 --> 00:04:50.720
were comparable between the two groups and those reported in pivotal trials in real-world studies.

00:04:51.280 --> 00:04:57.360
Again, in the unmatched cohort, we see comparable overall response rates

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:01.040
between the two groups, albeit lower CRR rates in the rapid group.

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:06.960
And then importantly, the time to best response in the rapid cohort was nearly half of the non-rapid

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:14.080
cohort at 34 days versus 62 days. And then probably most importantly, so in this propensity-matched

00:05:14.080 --> 00:05:19.280
analysis where we balance these covariates that we know can impact both CRS and ICANNs, as well as response rates and survival rates and survival rates between the two groups,

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:19.280
and then probably most importantly, so in this propensity-matched analysis where we balance these covariates that we know can impact both CRS and ICANNs, as well as response rates and survival rates between the two groups,

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:19.280
and then probably most importantly, so in this propensity-matched analysis where we balance these covariates that we know can impact both CRS and ICANNs, as well as response rates and survival rates between the two groups,

00:05:21.280 --> 00:05:22.480
and then probably most importantly, so in this propensity-matched analysis where we balance these covariates that we know can impact both CRS and ICANNs, as well as response rates and survival rates between the two groups,

00:05:22.480 --> 00:05:27.680
what we see is that there is no significant association between a rapid dose escalation

00:05:27.680 --> 00:05:31.440
and CRS or ICANNs, which is shown in that upper blue box.

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:36.480
And similarly, there was no significant association between a rapid dose escalation schedule

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:41.600
and an overall response rate and/or complete response rate shown in the lower orange box.

00:05:43.680 --> 00:05:48.960
And similarly, in this propensity-matched cohort, when we looked at PFS and OS,

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:50.880
although that we see the standard group,

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:51.280
which is shown in the lower orange box,

00:05:51.280 --> 00:05:52.880
which is shown in the pinkish color,

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:55.920
had numerically longer median PFS and OS,

00:05:55.920 --> 00:05:58.160
this was not statistically significant.

00:05:58.160 --> 00:06:03.680
And again, when we specifically looked at the association between a rapid dose escalation schedule,

00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:06.320
and sorry, that's a typo, it should say PFS and OS,

00:06:06.320 --> 00:06:08.160
there was no significant association.

00:06:09.360 --> 00:06:12.240
So, in conclusion, as it stands to our knowledge,

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:16.480
this is currently the largest real-world analysis of patients treated with Glofit and EPCO

00:06:16.480 --> 00:06:18.560
on a rapid dose escalation schedule.

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:20.880
And using a very robust statistical model

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:23.120
to account for confounding baseline features,

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:26.080
we saw that a rapid dose escalation schedule

00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:30.960
did not significantly impact CRS-ICANN's response rates or survival outcomes

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:34.000
when compared to a propensity-matched population of patients.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:38.000
And it also resulted in a shorter time to best response.

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:40.800
And then because I have 14 seconds,

00:06:40.800 --> 00:06:43.440
I'll skip ahead and just say our study supports the utilization

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:47.520
of a rapid dose escalation schedule for Glofit or EPCO

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:50.240
when treating patients with aggressive B-cell lymphoma.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:06:52.480
Okay.
